item.title: Iran Says It Launched First Military Satellite
item.description: Iran’s Revolutionary Guard said it launched its first military satellite into space, a move American officials have warned could advance Tehran’s missile capabilities, amid renewed tensions with the U.S.

item.title: Hong Kong Charges Teens With Murder Tied to Protests
item.description: Charges related to a man who was hit on the head by a brick thrown during an antigovernment protest last year is the most serious criminal indictment yet over the unrest.

item.title: Trump Warns Iran Against U.S. Navy Harassment
item.description: President Trump warned Iran Wednesday that he has instructed the U.S. Navy to ‘shoot down and destroy’ Iranian gunboats if they continue to harass American ships in the Persian Gulf.

item.title: Mortality Rates Tell True Tale of Coronavirus's Effect
item.description: Governments considering reopening economies frozen by restrictions to limit the spread of the new coronavirus are struggling to determine how deadly it is. With tests for the virus still in short supply, many analysts are looking to the blunter measure of total deaths.

item.title: Singapore Built a Virus App, but It Hasn't Worked So Far
item.description: As governments race to roll out contact-tracing apps to fight the pandemic, including an Apple-Google effort in the U.S., an early experiment in Singapore faces a big hurdle: getting people to sign up.

item.title: Millions of Europeans Are on Paid Leave. Governments Are Picking Up the Tab.
item.description: At least 18 million European workers have been idled over the past month, as the coronavirus pandemic cuts a widening swath through job markets and prompts governments to spend hundreds of billions of dollars to support laid-off workers.
